  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do insurance deductibles work?",
  "response": "Insurance deductibles are a key component of many types of insurance policies, including health, auto, and home insurance. Here\u2019s how they generally work:\n\n1. **Definition**: A deductible is the amount of money you must pay out of pocket before your insurance coverage kicks in. It is the portion of a claim that you are responsible for.\n\n2. **Payment**: When you file a claim, you are required to pay the deductible amount directly. After you pay the deductible, your insurance company will cover the remaining costs up to the policy's limit.\n\n3. **Types of Deductibles**:\n   - **Fixed Dollar Amount**: This is a set amount you pay, such as $500 or $1,000.\n   - **Percentage-Based**: Some deductibles are based on a percentage of the insured value, often seen in property insurance (e.g., 2% of the home's insured value).\n\n4. **Impact on Premiums**: Generally, higher deductibles lead to lower insurance premiums because you are taking on more risk. Conversely, lower deductibles result in higher premiums.\n\n5. **Annual vs. Per-Claim Deductibles**:\n   - **Annual Deductible**: Common in health insurance, where you pay the deductible amount once per year, regardless of the number of claims.\n   - **Per-Claim Deductible**: Often used in auto and home insurance, where you pay the deductible each time you file a claim.\n\n6. **Choosing a Deductible**: When selecting a deductible, consider your financial situation. Higher deductibles can reduce your premium, but you need to ensure you can afford to pay the deductible amount in the event of a claim.\n\n7. **Examples**:\n   - **Health Insurance**: If you have a $1,000 annual deductible, you must pay the first $1,000 of your medical expenses out of pocket each year before your insurance starts covering costs.\n   - **Auto Insurance**: If you have a $500 deductible and your car sustains $2,000 worth of damage, you pay $500, and your insurance covers the remaining $1,500.\n\nUnderstanding how deductibles work is crucial for managing your insurance costs and ensuring you have adequate coverage when you need it.",
